>\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' {{URL|www.dereksloan.ca}}\n;Policies:\n:;Economic\n:*Repeal the carbon tax<ref>{{cite web |title=The Unconstiutional Carbon Tax |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/carbon_tax |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Repeal Bill C-69 (\"The modernization of the National Energy Board and Canadian Environmental Assessment Agency\") and C-48 (\"An Act respecting the regulation of vessels that transport crude oil or persistent oil\") to promote pipeline construction<ref>{{cite web |title=Energy and Resource Development |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/energy_and_resource_development |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:;Foreign\n:*Remove abortion funding from foreign aid<ref name=\"life\">{{cite web |title=Respect For Human Life |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/respect_for_human_life |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Reduce annual immigration rates from 350,000 to 150,000<ref name=\"Immigration\">{{cite web |title=Immigration |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/immigration |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Increase funding for border patrol<ref name=\"Immigration\"/>\n:*Increase the quota for privately sponsored refugees<ref name=\"Immigration\"/>\n:*Oppose [[UNDRIP]]<ref name=\"Soverienty\">{{cite web |title=Canadian Soverienty |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/canadian_sovereignty |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Withdraw from the [[Paris Agreement]]<ref name=\"Soverienty\"/>\n:*Withdraw from the UN [[Global Compact for Migration]]<ref name=\"Immigration\"/>\n:;Military\n:*Meet the 2% of GDP targets for defence spending set out by [[NATO]] within five years<ref>{{cite web |title=A Strong Canada Through A Strong Defense (sic) |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/strong_defense |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:;Social\n:*Encourage parliamentary votes on abortion<ref name=\"life\"/>\n:*Protect free speech by opposing Bill C-16 (which adds gender expression and gender identity as protected grounds to the Canadian Human Rights Act)<ref>{{cite web |title=Free Speech in Canada |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/free_speech_in_canada |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Revoke the citizenship of dual citizens who are convicted terrorists<ref>{{cite web |title=A Safe Canada\u2014Fighting Terrorism |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/fighting_terrorism |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Raise the minimum age required to purchase cannabis to 25<ref>{{cite web |title=Marijuana |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/marijuana |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Decriminalize non-victim, non-violent firearm offences<ref name=\"firearms\">{{cite web |title=Firearms |url=https://www.dereksloan.ca/firearms |website=Derek Sloan for Leader|access-date = 19 April 2020}}</ref>\n:*Completely review the Firearms Act<ref name=\"firearms\"/>\n:*Repeal Bills C-71 (\"An Act to amend certain Acts and Regulations in relation to firearms\")(2019), C-42 (\"An Act to amend the Firearms Act and the Criminal Code\")(2015), C-68 (\"An Act to amend the Fisheries Act and other Acts in consequence\")(1995), C-17 (\"An Act to amend the Yukon Environmental and Socio-economic Assessment Act and to make a consequential amendment to another Act\") (1991), and C-51 (\"An Act to amend the Criminal Code and the Department of Justice Act and to make consequential amendments to another Act\") (1977)<ref name=\"firearms\"/>\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Derek Sloan\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n;'''Senators:'''\n;'''Provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n*[[Brad Trost]] (MP for [[Saskatoon\u2014University]], 2004\u20132019)<ref name=Trost/>\n;'''Former Senators:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Other prominent individuals:\n*[[Richard D\u00e9carie]] (Former Deputy Chief of Staff to then-[[Leader of the Opposition (Canada)|Opposition Leader]] [[Stephen Harper]]; former Chief of Staff & Senior Advisor to then-[[Premier of Quebec|Premier]] [[Jean Charest]]; Conservative Party of Canada leadership contestant, 2020)<ref name=\"SloanDecarie\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DerekSloanCPC/status/1235583704845758464|title=Honoured to receive the endorsement and support of Richard D\u00e9carie, who continues to be a strong voice for Quebec and for all Canadian conservatives. #cdnpoli|last=Sloan|first=Derek|date=4 March 2020|website=Twitter|url-status=live|access-date=5 March 2020}}</ref>'''\n;'''Organizations: \n*[[Campaign Life Coalition]]<ref name=\"auto3\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CampaignLife/status/1220096631003058176?s=20|title=Derek Sloan would make a great CPC Leader.|date=22 January 2020|language=en|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n==Withdrew or failed to qualify==\n\n===Failed to qualify as authorized contestants===\nApproved applicants who failed to pass the second qualification stage that required 2,000 signatures and the submission of the full $100,000 compliance fee and at least $50,000 of the entrance fee by March 25, 2020 or who disqualified between Stage 1 and Stage 2.<ref name=note/>\n====Marilyn Gladu====\n[[File:Marilyn Gladu.png|thumb|upright|Marilyn Gladu]]\n;Background\n[[Marilyn Gladu]], 57, is the MP for [[Sarnia\u2014Lambton]] (2015\u2013present), and was the Shadow Minister of Health (2017\u20132020),<ref>{{cite web|url=https://mattjeneroux.ca/news-release-mp-matt-jeneroux-named-shadow-minister-of-health/|title=NEWS RELEASE: MP Matt Jeneroux named Shadow Minister of Health|date=27 January 2020|access-date=27 January 2020}}</ref> Shadow Minister of Science (2015\u20132017). Prior to entering politics, she was an engineer for [[Dow Chemical Company|Dow Chemical]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/MariekeWalsh/status/1205515327448195072|title=Ontario Conservative MP @MPMarilynGladu says she's considering running for leader, is pro-choice, would walk in a Pride Parade and won't fight the carbon tax.|first=Marieke|last=Walsh|date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/windsor/sarnia-lambton-conservative-mp-not-ruling-out-leadership-run-1.5396090|title=Sarnia-Lambton Conservative MP considering leadership run, will confirm decision after winter holidays|publisher=CBC News|access-date=14 December 2019|date=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 9 January 2020<ref>{{cite news |last1=Thibedeau |first1=Hannah |title=MP Marilyn Gladu is running for the Conservative leadership |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/marilyn-gladu-conservative-leadership-1.5420743 |accessdate=9 January 2020 |publisher=CBC News |date=9 January 2020}}</ref>\n:'''Candidacy suspended:''' 25 March 2020\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' https://www.marilyngladu.ca\n:\n\n====Rudy Husny====\n;Background\nRudy Husny is Director of Stakeholder Relations in the Office of the Leader of the Official Opposition and candidate in [[Outremont (electoral district)|Outremont]] in 2011 and 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/rudyhusny/ |title=Security Verification |publisher=LinkedIn |date= |accessdate=2020-02-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/rudyhusny/status/1207805233327267840?s=12|title=To help play a role in getting us there, I am strongly considering running for the Leadership of the Conservative Party of Canada |first=Rudy|last=Husny|date=19 December 2019}}</ref>\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 8 February 2020<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/conservative-leadership-candidates-fight-for-support-at-ontario-pc-convention|title=Conservative leadership candidates fight for support at Ontario PC convention &#124; National Post|date=23 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/canada/conservative-leadership-contenders-set-to-take-the-stage-in-nova-scotia|title=Conservative leadership contenders set to take the stage in Nova Scotia &#124; Ottawa Citizen|date=8 February 2020}}</ref>\n:'''Candidacy suspended:''' 19 March 2020<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/rudy-husny-leadership-deadline-1.5503646|title=Tory leadership candidate says he's out of the race if deadlines don't change|last=Levitz|first=Stephanie|date=19 March 2020|website=CBC News|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=19 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nWithdrew due to tight election timeline and rules. Husny cited the ongoing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|2020 coronavirus pandemic crisis]] as his stated reason for suspending his campaign, saying it is just not right to ask people for money during a public health emergency.<ref name=\":6\" />\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' https://www.gorudygo.com/\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Rudy Husny\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n;'''Senators:'''\n;'''Provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n;'''Former Senators:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Other prominent individuals:''' \n* Aron Seal (Conservative Party of Canada leadership contestant, 2020).<ref name=\"twitter seal\">{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/aronseal/status/1232379665181896704|title=Dear @CPC_HQ Members\n|first=Aron|last=Seal|date=25 February 2020}}</ref>\n;'''Organizations:'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n====Jim Karahalios====\n;Background\nJim Karahalios is a corporate lawyer and founder of activist groups \"Axe The Carbon Tax\" and \"Take Back Our PC Party\". He sued the Ontario PC party after narrowly losing an election in November 2018 for party president, but the case has not yet been tried. He is accusing the Ontario PC party of ballot stuffing in that election.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://toronto.ctvnews.ca/ontario-pc-member-who-is-suing-party-announces-bid-for-federal-party-leader-1.4786467|title=Ontario PC member who is suing party announces bid for federal party leader|first=Katherine|last=DeClerq|date=28 January 2020|website=Toronto}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 28 January 2020<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n:'''Disqualified:''' 20 March 2020\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' [https://www.jimkarahalios.ca/ Jim Karahalios for Conservative Party Leader]\n;Policies:\nKarahalios was accused of anti-Muslim bigotry after issuing a letter accusing rival candidate Erin O'Toole of promoting \"[[sharia law]].\" Karahalios wrote that Erin O'Toole's campaign chair, Walied Soliman, had advocated for sharia law in an interview<ref>{{cite news|title=Opinion: Islamic Finance|url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/opinion/islamic-finance/article1077243/|accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Globe and Mail |date=May 31, 2007}}</ref> and had previously participated in the Ontario PC party's lawsuit against Karahalios as a private citizen, a lawsuit which was dismissed by the court as \"[[strategic litigation against public participation]]\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Benzie |first1=Robert |title=Party activist who opposed Patrick Brown gets apology from interim PC leader |url=https://www.thestar.com/news/queenspark/2018/03/01/party-activist-who-opposed-patrick-brown-gets-apology-from-interim-pc-leader.html |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=Toronto Star |date=March 1, 2018}}</ref> The Urban Alliance on Race Relations called on the Conservative Party to disqualify Karahalios's candidacy.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Platt |first1=Brian |title=Tory leadership candidate Jim Karahalios accused of anti-Muslim 'bigotry' over letter |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/perceived-anti-muslim-comment-lands-tory-leadership-candidate-jim-karahalios-in-bigotry-row |accessdate=March 20, 2020 |work=National Post |date=March 12, 2020}}</ref>\n\nKarahalios obtained the required 3,000 verified signatures and collected $300,000 for the entrance fee, but CPC officers refused to put his name on the ballot. The exact reasons for Karahalios's disqualification were not released.<ref>{{cite news |title=Cambridge's Jim Karahalios calls disqualification from Conservative leadership 'unlawful' |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/kitchener-waterloo/jim-karahalios-conservative-leadership-disqualification-1.5506875 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=CBC |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref> Karahalios is contesting the disqualification in court.  <ref>{{cite news |title='We are going to court': Jim Karahalios after Conservative leadership disqualification|url=https://www.kitchenertoday.com/local-news/we-are-going-to-court-jim-karahalios-after-conservative-leadership-disqualification-2196469|accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work= |date=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Jim Karahalios\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n;'''Senators:'''\n;'''Provincial politicians:'''\n*[[Belinda Karahalios]] (Ontario MPP for [[Cambridge (provincial electoral district)|Cambridge]], wife of the candidate)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ColinDMello/status/1222130270264070144|title=NEW: Jim Karahalios, husband of Ontatio MPP Belinda Karahalios, is running for CPC leader.|first=Colin D'Mello|last=CTVNews|date=28 January 2020}}</ref> \n\n;'''Municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n;'''Former Senators:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Other prominent individuals:'''\n;'''Organizations:''' [[Campaign Life Coalition]]<ref name=\"kara\">{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/conservative-leadership-field-grows-to-six-as-derek-sloan-jim-karahalios-become-official-candidates|title=Conservative leadership field grows to six as Derek Sloan, Jim Karahalios become official candidates &#124; National Post|first=Canadian|last=Politics|date=26 February 2020}}</ref>\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n====Rick Peterson====\n[[File:Rick-Peterson (portrait).jpg|thumb|upright|Rick Peterson]]\n;Background\nRick Peterson, {{age|1955|9|3}}, is a venture capitalist, party fundraiser, principal of Peterson Capital, and a former candidate for leadership of the [[British Columbia Conservative Party]]. He was a member of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservatives]] at the time of the merger. He ran and placed 12th in the [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|2017 Conservative leadership election]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hilltimes.com/2019/12/18/scheer-exit-opens-door-for-reset-say-members-who-welcome-the-chance-to-spring-clean/228854|title=Scheer exit opens door for reset, say members who welcome the chance 'to spring clean'|first=The Hill|last=Times|date=18 December 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/rick-peterson-conservative-leadership-1.5436247?cmp=rss|title=Businessman Rick Peterson is taking a second run at the Conservative leadership|last=Thibedeau|first=Hannah|date=Jan 22, 2020|website=CBC|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 22 January 2020<ref name=\":0\" />\n:'''Candidacy suspended:''' 20 March 2020<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.rickcpc.ca/statement_on_the_conservative_party_of_canada_leadership_race|title=Statement on the Conservative Party of Canada Leadership Race|last=Peterson|first=Rick|date=20 March 2020|website=Rick Peterson: Conservative Leader 2020|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 March 2020}}</ref>\nWithdrew due to tight election timeline and rules. Peterson also cited the ongoing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|2020 coronavirus pandemic crisis]] as his stated reason for suspending his campaign.<ref name=\":7\" />\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' {{URL|rickcpc.ca}}\n;Policies: \n*Implement a 15% federal [[flat tax]]<ref name=\"petersonnp\">{{cite news |title=Rick Peterson looks to shake up the Conservative leadership race with flat tax plan |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/rick-peterson-looks-to-shake-up-the-conservative-leadership-race-with-flat-tax-plan |accessdate=January 29, 2020 |work=National Post |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n*Eliminate the federal corporate income tax\n*Repeal of [[Bill C-48]]<ref name=\"petersonnp\" />\n*Replace the federal [[carbon tax]] with a levy on heavy emitters<ref name=\"petersonnp\" />\n*End supply management\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Rick Peterson\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n;'''Senators:'''\n*[[Stephen Greene (politician)|Stephen Greene]] (Senator for [[Halifax Regional Municipality|Halifax]]-[[Citadel Hill (Fort George)|The Citadel]], [[Nova Scotia]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/RickCPC/posts/2974751252569301:0|title=I'm honoured and grateful to have Senator Stephen Greene supporting my leadership campaign. Thank you, Senator!|first=Rick|last=Peterson|date=7 February 2020}}</ref>\n;'''Provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n;'''Former Senators:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n*[[Lorne Mayencourt]] (Peterson's campaign manager; BC MLA for [[Vancouver-Burrard]] 2001-2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RPSuitsandBoots/status/1220865760119013376?s=20|title=Stoked to have this man running our @CPC_HQ leadership drive.|first=Rick|last=Peterson|date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Other prominent individuals:'''\n*[[Mark Mullins (economist)|Mark Mullins]] (economist; former executive director of [[Fraser Institute]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/RickCPC/posts/3010054952372264|title=Leading Economist Mark Mullins Endorses Peterson Tax Plan|first=Rick|last=Peterson|date=24 February 2020}}</ref>\n;'''Organizations:'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n===Failed to qualify as approved applicants===\nDeclared candidates who failed to pass the first qualification stage by obtaining at least 1,000 signatures, submit at least $25,000 of the entrance fee by February 27, 2020 and/or pass the vetting process.<ref name=note>{{Cite web|url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/conservative-leadership-notebook-after-first-deadline-up-to-nine-candidates-contend-for-the-throne|title=Conservative leadership notebook: After first deadline, up to nine candidates contend for the throne &#124; National Post|first=Canadian|last=Politics|date=28 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n====Richard D\u00e9carie====\n;Background\n[[Richard D\u00e9carie]], {{age|1959|9|20}}, was the Deputy Chief of Staff to then-[[Leader of the Opposition (Canada)|Opposition Leader]] [[Stephen Harper]] and Chief of Staff & Senior Advisor to then-[[Premier of Quebec|Premier]] [[Jean Charest]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Alec_Castonguay/status/1214539411247042567|title=[in French] L'ancien conseiller de Stephen Harper en 2004-2005, @RichardDECARIE|last=Castonguay|first=Alec|date=7 January 2020|website=Twitter|url-status=live|access-date=7 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Plattdecarie\">{{cite news |title=Former Conservative Party staffer prepares to enter leadership race as the 'so-con' candidate |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/former-conservative-party-staffer-set-to-enter-leadership-race-as-the-so-con-candidate |accessdate=January 22, 2020 |work=National Post |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 30 January 2020 <ref name=\"Plattdecarie\"/>\n;Notes:D\u00e9carie advocated for social conservative values.<ref name=\"Plattdecarie\"/> \u00a0\"I think 'LGBTQ' is a Liberal term. I don't talk about people that way, I talk about persons, and I think we all need the full respect for being a human being.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/video?clipId=1882276&jwsource=fb>|accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=CTV News |date=January 22, 2020}}</ref> When asked by an interviewer whether \"being gay\" was a \"choice\" or not, D\u00e9carie said that it was. \u00a0This answer lead to calls by Kory Teneycke, a former senior aide to both Stephen Harper and Doug Ford, that he be barred from running.<ref name=\"Plattdecarie2\">{{cite news |last1=Platt |first1=Brian |title=How the Conservatives' Leadership Contestant Questionnaire could derail Richard D\u00e9carie |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/how-the-conservatives-leadership-contestant-questionnaire-could-derail-richard-decarie |accessdate=January 30, 2020 |work=National 3 |date=January 30, 2020}}</ref> D\u00e9carie acquired the required number of signatures and paid the deposit but was disqualified by the party following his interview with the nomination committee.<ref>{{cite news |title=Conservative Party bars controversial candidate Richard D\u00e9carie from leadership race |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/richard-decarie-blocked-from-running-conservative-leadership-race-1.5481159 |accessdate=February 29, 2020 |work=CBC News |date=February 29, 2020}}</ref> Endorsed Derek Sloan.<ref name=\"SloanDecarie\" />\n\n====Clayton Knutzon====\n;Background \nClayton Knutzon is a former [[Freedom Conservative Party of Alberta|Freedom Conservative Party]] candidate in [[Alberta]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/calgary/2019/03/24/former-freedom-conservative-candidate-doubles-down-on-islamophobic-commentary-after-removal.html|title=Former Freedom Conservative candidate doubles down on Islamophobic commentary after removal &#124; The Star|website=Toronto Star}}</ref><ref name=\"auto1\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ClaytonCanoes/status/1208626364565213184|title=I am Running for leader of the #CPC - just waiting for the nomination papers from the @CPC_HQ #hoc #pnpcbc #cbcnn Am I the first to formally announce? #cdnpoli|first=Clayton|last=Knutzon|date=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 22 December 2019<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n====Bobby Singh====\n;Background \nBobby Singh is a Toronto businessman and the former CPC candidate for [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge Park]], [[Ontario]] in the [[2019 Canadian federal election|2019 election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/toronto/bobby-singh-conservative-leadership-1.5431035|title=Toronto businessman, failed Conservative candidate Bobby Singh entering CPC leadership race|date=17 January 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=19 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 15 January 2020<ref name=\"auto2\"/>\n\n====Irvin Studin====\n;Background\nIrvin Studin is a senior fellow at the [[University of Toronto]]\u2019s [[Munk School of Global Affairs and Public Policy]], a [[Rhodes Scholar]], former professional soccer player with the [[Toronto Lynx]], and served in the [[Privy Council Office (Canada)|Privy Council Office]] between 2002 and 2006.<ref name=\"studin\">{{cite news |title=Conservative leadership hopeful wants 100 million people in Canada |url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2020/02/27/conservative-leadership-hopeful-wants-100-million-people-in-canada.html |accessdate=February 27, 2020 |work=Toronto Star |date=February 27, 2020}}</ref>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 25 February 2020<ref name=\"studin\"/>\n\n===Withdrawn prior to February 27, 2020===\n\n====Bryan Brulotte====\n;Background\nCEO and chair of employment firm MaxSys Staffing and Consulting (1993\u2013present), deputy chief of staff to [[Paul Dick]] (1993), [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada|Progressive Conservative]] candidate for [[Lanark-Carleton]] in 2000.<ref name=\"brulotte\">{{cite news |last1=Brewster |first1=Murray |title=Conservative leadership gets committed candidate as political heavyweights mull options |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/conservative-leadership-race-brulotte-1.5397367 |accessdate=16 December 2019 |publisher=[[CBC News]] |